<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-03-30T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-03-30T16:00:00-05:00" n="497" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d497">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/2738: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Morris</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-03-30T17:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">March 30,
                                            1920—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>112. Your 124, March 26, 11 a.m.</p>
                            <p>Lamont’s proposed exchange of notes has the approval of the
                                Department. The Embassies at London and Paris are being instructed
                                to advise the respective Foreign Offices thereof and to urge the
                                desirability of facilitating a prompt agreement by indicating a
                                similar approval on the part of the British and French Governments
                                and groups. The British Government has been particularly requested
                                to waive its protest against the exclusion from the consortium of
                                the three lines west of the South Manchuria Railway.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>